## 3. `df_question_errors.csv` — Error Taxonomy

Maps questions to the errors a student is likely to make. Each question maps to 1–3 anticipated errors. These are the "traps" an examiner designed into the question.

**Rows:** 5,522 | **Unique errors:** 286 | **Error types:** 3

| Column | Type | Description |
|--------|------|-------------|
| `question_id` | string | Foreign key → `df_master.question_id` |
| `error_id` | string | Unique error identifier. Format: `ERR_M_{topic_num}_{seq}` |
| `error_name` | string | Concise error label (e.g., "Domain-blind solving") |
| `error_type` | string | One of three categories (see below) |
| `description` | string | Detailed explanation of how and why the error occurs |

**Error type categories:**

| Type | Meaning | Student implication |
|------|---------|---------------------|
| Conceptual error | Student lacks the underlying theory | Needs to re-study the concept |
| Setup error | Student knows the theory but fails to model the problem correctly | Needs to practice problem translation |
| Procedural error | Student sets up correctly but makes a mechanical mistake | Needs computation practice under time pressure |

**Sample row:**
```
question_id: Q_M_15_002
error_id: ERR_M_16_002
error_name: Domain-blind solving
error_type: Setup error
description: "The student solves the logarithmic equation algebraically but fails to verify that all solutions satisfy base > 0, base ≠ 1, and argument > 0 constraints, reporting extraneous solutions."
```

